Let the roots of $x^3 - Ax^2 + Bx - C = 0$ be $r_1, r_2, r_3.$  Then the roots of $x^3 + Px^2 + Qx - 19 = 0$ are $r_1 + 1, r_2 + 1, r_3 + 1.$
By Vieta's formulas, we have
\begin{align*} r_1 + r_2 + r_3 &= A \\ r_1 r_2 + r_1 r_3 + r_2 r_3 &= B \\ r_1 r_2 r_3 &= C. \end{align*}
Also,
\begin{align*} (r_1 + 1) + (r_2 + 1) + (r_3 + 1) &= -P \\ (r_1 + 1)(r_2 + 1) + (r_1 + 1)(r_3 + 1) + (r_2 + 1)(r_3 + 1) &= Q \\ (r_1 + 1)(r_2 + 1)(r_3 + 1) &= 19. \end{align*}
From the first equation, $r_1 + r_2 + r_3 + 3 = -P$, so $A + 3 = -P,$ and $P = -A - 3.$

From the second equation,
\begin{align*} (r_1 r_2 + r_1 r_3 + r_2 r_3) + (r_1 + r_2 + r_3) + 1 \cdot 3 &= Q \\ B + A + 3 &= Q \\ Q &= A + B + 3. \end{align*}
From the third equation,
\begin{align*} (r_1 r_2 r_3) + (r_1 r_2 + r_1 r_3 + r_2 r_3) + (r_1 + r_2 + r_3) + 1 &= 19 \\ C + B + A + 3 &= 19 \\ C + B + A &= 16. \end{align*}
We want to find $A + B + C.$  We have $C + B + A = 16.$  Therefore, $A + B + C = 16.$

Final Answer: $\boxed{16}$

